{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520100"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13140"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13140"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.18,0.37,0.2,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107081"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89545"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"738"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"3399"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6524"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31754"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107081"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a 12 hour history of severe abdominal pain. Her medical history includes cirrhosis secondary to alcohol use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is pale and sweating profusely. Her blood pressure is 90/50 mmHg, pulse 130/min and temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her abdomen is distended and tender on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer venous blood gas reveals a haemoglobin of 70 g/L and lactate of 5 mmol/L. Bedside ultrasound shows evidence of free fluid in the abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is immediately given 2L of normal saline. Her blood pressure is now 94/55 mmHg and pulse 120/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Placement of a Sengstaken-Blakemore tube","Immediate endoscopic therapy","Transfusion with blood products","Administration of vasopressors","CT scan of the abdomen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s clinical presentation of shock, in combination with her history of cirrhosis, points strongly towards a variceal hemorrhage. Despite the administration of crystalloid fluids, her haemodynamic status remains compromised. Transfusion with \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood products\u003C/strong\u003E, including packed red blood cells (to enhance oxygen-carrying capacity and replace lost blood) and platelets and fresh frozen plasma (to counteract potential coagulopathy), is imperative. Cirrhosis frequently results in anaemia and coagulopathy due to the liver\u0027s diminished production of clotting factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThough both \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate endoscopic therapy\u003C/strong\u003E and the deployment of a \u003Cstrong\u003ESengstaken-Blakemore tube\u003C/strong\u003E are treatment modalities for variceal bleeding, they are not appropriate choices for a patient in her current unstable state. Whilst her low haemoglobin is suggestive of active gastrointestinal haemorrhage, it should not be assumed that this is variceal in origin. In some 40% of patients with cirrhosis and varices, when acute bleeding occurs, it comes from another source. She needs stabilisation before definitive treatment can proceed. The situation does not warrant a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E, and the delay in arranging and performing such a diagnostic test could potentially further destabilise her condition. Moreover, upper gastrointestinal bleeding rarely necessitates a CT scan as part of the diagnostic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasopressors\u003C/strong\u003E are not the prime solution in this case. While vasopressors can elevate blood pressure, they do so by causing vasoconstriction, which reduces blood flow to peripheral tissues. By doing this, they can inadvertently exacerbate ischaemia, particularly in the gut, kidneys, and other vital organs. As a result, the lactic acidosis may worsen due to increased anaerobic metabolism in tissues with compromised blood flow. In the context of haemorrhagic shock, the key issue is the volume, not the vascular tone. Vasopressors do not address the root problem, which is the loss of blood volume.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with haemorrhagic shock who do not respond to initial crystalloid resuscitation, transfusion with blood products should be considered.","In patients with liver disease presenting with hemodynamic instability and evidence of intra-abdominal fluid, consider variceal haemorrhage as a potential cause."],"references":["Garcia-Tsao G, Abraldes JG, Berzigotti A, Bosch J. Portal hypertensive bleeding in cirrhosis: Risk stratification, diagnosis, and management: 2016 practice guidance by the American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases. Hepatology. 2017;65(1):310-335."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89545"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13140"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89545"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T06:47:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T06:47:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107081"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attri